= Security =

* <u>'''GNOME Website Extensions:'''</u> GNOME allows installing extensions via an <code>Install</code> button on its website. Example: [https://extensions.gnome.org/extension/1160/dash-to-panel/ Dash to Panel extension]
** <u>Digital signature verification:</u> Does it perform digital software signature verification?
* <u>'''Security Risks in Default Installation:'''</u> The standard GNOME setup includes numerous features, which may lead to security vulnerabilities.
** <u>Anchor:</u> {{anchor|show=true|1-Click RCE on GNOME (CVE-2023-43641) in file indexing service}}
** <u>'''File Download Vulnerabilities:'''</u> Simple file downloads have, in the past, led to remote code execution.
** <u>'''Link Click Vulnerabilities:'''</u> Clicking a link on a website has, in the past, led to remote code execution.
*** <u>'''Related Blog Post:'''</u> See the blog post: [https://github.blog/2023-10-09-coordinated-disclosure-1-click-rce-on-gnome-cve-2023-43641/ Coordinated disclosure: 1-Click RCE on GNOME (CVE-2023-43641)]
*** <u>'''Demonstration Video:'''</u> Watch the short video here: [https://github.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/CVE-2023-43641-poc.mp4 CVE-2023-43641 proof-of-concept video]
*** <u>'''News Report:'''</u> LWN: [https://lwn.net/Articles/947288/ Remote execution in the GNOME tracker]
** <u>'''Tracker-Miner Daemon Concerns:'''</u> GNOME runs tracker-miner, a daemon that parses all user-downloaded files, which has had such vulnerabilities in the past. Such daemons should not run by default.
** <u>'''Compromised Theoretical Security:'''</u> Theoretical security benefits from Wayland can be undermined by poor security practices.
* <u>'''Social Account Integration:'''</u> Privacy and security concerns exist regarding the integration of social accounts.

= Reasons Against Using a Minimal Desktop Environment Without Its Bad Stuff =

While it might be theoretically possible to avoid GNOME's undesirable aspects by selectively using only core packages like the window manager and systray, this approach is not without notable drawbacks.

Selectively using GNOME components, such as the window manager and systray, while concurrently issuing warnings about other standard GNOME functionalities, creates contradictions and practical challenges. This methodology seems counterintuitive: utilizing only specific parts of GNOME (like the window manager and systray) while needing to add warnings and disclaimers against its standard, documented features in user documentation and support requests.

For example, GNOME's recommended method for installing the Clipboard Indicator involves visiting [https://extensions.gnome.org/extension/779/clipboard-indicator/ extensions.gnome.org Clipboard Indicator] and clicking 'Install'. However, this raises a question: what is the secure alternative that avoids browser interactions and includes digital software verification? As of this writing, this remains unclear.

For instance, consider a user query:

{{quotation
